4 MeV tandem dynamitron
The proton and neutron channels were
studied in the 6Li+6Li reaction using metallic
lithium target. In the close vicinity of the target a
liquid nitrogen cold trap was installed to reduce
carbon build-up, and lithium hydroxide formation. In
case of the proton channel angular distributions were
measured for 0.58-175 degrees varying the beam energy
between 2 and 16 MeV in steps of 200 keV. For
detection of the protons at forward angles, silicon
surface barrier detectors in dE-E telescope
configuration were used. The thickness of the dE
detector was sufficient to stop alpha particles, thus
with an anti-coincidence requirement between the dE
and E detectors, it was possible to obtain clean
proton spectra. At backward angles, single surface
barrier detectors wrapped in Al foil were used. For
the measurement at 0.58 degree, a single detector was
mounted on the beam axis behind the target. The
target in this case had a 0.1 mm thick Ta backing,
which stopped the recoiling 6Li nuclei and all
ejectiles but protons. In case of the neutron channel,
pulsed beam was used with FWHM of 1.4 ns and
repetition rate of 400 ns. Excitation functions were
measured for energies 4.75-12.0 MeV in steps of 250
keV. Below 8 MeV beam energy, 100 ug/cm**2 thick Li
targets on 0.1 mm Ta backings were used, while at
higher energies targets with 130 ug/cm**2 Li layer
thickness were chosen. The neutrons were detected by
N213 liquid scintillators. Pulse shape discrimination
was used to suppress photon background.
Metallic 6Li targets, made by vacuum
deposition onto very clean Ti and Ni backings. The
thickness of the Li-6 layer was determined by
Rutherford scattering of 58Ni(4+) ions, and it was
found to be 30-150 ug/cm**2. The thickness of the
backings varied between 50 and 200 ug/cm**2.
No detailed error analysis was provided.
